The President of Russia, Vladimir Putin, has signed a law imposing administrative liability for the violation of the time and procedure for the payment of goods (work, services) in the procurement of public and municipal needs.
The Act is intended to address the very acute problem of non-performance by clients in the conduct of public and municipal procurement.
Two years ago, the situation in which businessmen were unable to receive payment under existing State and municipal contracts was widespread.
At the same time, the President of Russia instructed the Office of the Attorney-General of the Russian Federation to take the problem into special control.
Because the businessmen themselves could not deal with unscrupulous clients who had entered into unfunded contracts, tried to avoid their obligations to pay, and included illegal terms in the contracts.
The problem was systemic in the country as a whole.
Since 2015, in order to protect the rights of businessmen to be paid under public orders, the Office of the Public Prosecutor has submitted 9,000 submissions, with the result that 4,500 officials have been disciplined and 533 administrative officers, and 75 files have been submitted to the investigative bodies for the purpose of organizing procedural checks, 46 of which have led to criminal proceedings.
As a result, more than 66 billion roubles of business debt was paid.
These huge sums have not been accumulated as a result of the non-payment of multi-billion-dollar contracts.
Numerous, systematic delays in the payment of services to entrepreneurs for much more modest amounts have led to huge debts.
Here's the case.
The manager of the small company won a competition for social transport services for a number of millions of roubles.
The man invested all his working money, fully met his obligations, but did not get the money on time.
The result is an increasing financial coma of salary, tax, credit that would have led to bankruptcy if the entrepreneur had not sought the help of the Public Prosecutor's Office.
The problem has now been resolved as far as possible in a number of regions.
However, as of the first half of 2017, the total amount of public and municipal debt identified by the procurators of the constituent entities of the Russian Federation was about 27.4 billion roubles.
In regions where debt indicators continue to reach critical levels, the Public Prosecutor's Office is working in a manual crisis management environment.
The Attorney-General personally holds visiting meetings with the local authorities to deal in detail with all the violations that the procurators have revealed and to deal with them without delay.
Such operational meetings have already taken place this year in Jaroslavla and Yekaterinburg.
The implementation of Federal Act No. 189-FZ “On the amendment of the Code of Administrative Offences in order to establish the administrative liability of the employer's officials for the violation of the time and procedure for the payment of goods (work, services) in the conduct of public and municipal purchases”, signed last week by the President of the Russian Federation, will improve the quality of the discipline of public clients.
The draft law was drafted by the Ministry of Economic Development of Russia at the initiative of the Attorney-General ' s Office.
The new law will supplement the Code of Administrative Offences with an article which provides for a fine of 30,000 to 50,000 roubles for the violation by the employer of the time and procedure for the payment of goods, works and services in public and municipal procurement.
If an official had already been subject to administrative punishment for a similar offence, he or she would be disqualified for a period of between one and two years.
All the procurators of the constituent entities of the Russian Federation have already been instructed to ensure that these legislative innovations are applied in practice.
Civil Rights Unit issued a travel warning to Missouri.
The National Association for the Advancement of Colored People has issued a warning to colored people traveling to Missouri because of discriminatory state policies and racist attacks.
The group's statement is as follows: “Warning for travelers of the National Association for the Advancement of the Colored Population, valid until August 28, 2017, calls on African American travelers, visitors and citizens of Missouri to be particularly alert and to be more cautious in traveling around the state in connection with a number of suspicious racist incidents that have recently taken place all over the state and have been brought here.”
According to the National Association for the Advancement of the Colored Population, the recent Missouri law, which made it more difficult for people to win claims of discrimination, and the fact that state law enforcement authorities disproportionately target members of minorities.
“You are subject to human rights violations.
They are stopped on the roads because of their skin color, beaten and killed,” Rhode Chapel, president of the National Association for the Advancement of the Colored Population of Missouri, said to the newspaper Kansas City Star.
“We hear complaints more often than ever.”
This is the first warning of this kind announced by the organization to the state of the United States.
The Group referred to incidents such as the racial humiliation of black students at Missouri University and the death of 20-year-old Tori Sanders, a black man from Tennessee.
Sanders died under suspicious circumstances earlier this year after he ran out of gas on his trip to the state, and Missouri State Police arrested him without charge of a crime.
The warning also refers to a recent report by the Attorney General of Missouri State, according to which it is 75 per cent more likely to be stopped on the road for black drivers than for white drivers.
“The aim of the warning is to make people aware of the situation and to alert their relatives and friends and colleagues to what might happen in Missouri,” said Chapel.
“People must be trained in one way or another, whether they will take the money to bail or tell their families that they are traveling through state territory.”
According to the latest FBI hate crime report, there were 100 hate crimes reported in Missouri in 2015, making the state the 16th state in terms of the number of such violations.
A travel warning is also a response to the new Missouri State Act, which will make it more difficult to bring a case against a legal person for housing or work discrimination.
Previously, the American Civil Liberties Union (ALU) had issued warnings to travelers in Texas and Arizona after the state had enacted new immigration control laws, which required local law enforcement agencies to arrest people for violating immigration laws, which ACLU believed should have increased the number of racial checks.
Moving warnings are usually issued by the Department of State for other countries, but more recently public organizations have resorted to this measure in response to certain laws and trends within the US.
