This is a rare opportunity to look at daily life in the highlands of Papua, the former Dutch colony, which was joined by Indonesia in 1969 after a dubious referendum, when only 1,026 elders were forced to vote in public by raising their hands in front of the occupying forces.
The current movement for independence from the Netherlands had quickly turned its anger against the Government of Jakarta, which maintained strict control over the region, preventing foreign journalists and human rights defenders.
In 2003, the province was officially divided into Papua and West Papua, and the independent State of Papua New Guinea occupies the eastern part of the island.
Anarotali is a city as remote as an abandoned city; the road includes a one-and-a-half-hour flight from Jayapur, the provincial administrative center, to Nabeer, and a five-hour shake in a hired car.
There's no public transport here.
The city, with a population of about 19,000, consists of wooden houses surrounded by bamboo fences; roofs of corrugated steel are painted with rust in a variety of red-coloured shades.
Few Indonesians, let alone journalists, and almost none of the foreigners, have come here.
Prior to the arrival of Christian missionaries, the pope had worshipped a god named Uga Tameo.
There have been other changes.
“We were unfavorable to wear these clothes,” Deguei tells us, pointing to his bright, hand-cold turban, dark skirt, and bright shirt.
"We used to wear only leaves on the body."
Papua is the poorest province in Indonesia, 28 per cent of its population live below the poverty line, and child mortality and literacy rates are among the worst in Asia.
But it's also Indonesian gold land.
The world's largest and most lucrative gold mine, Grasberg, owned by Freeport McMoran, is only 60 miles from Pania, a high-rise province about the size of New Jersey, where 153,000 people live.
In 2015 alone, Freeport recovered about $3.1 billion in gold and copper.
In addition, Papua can boast forest reserves valued at $78 billion.
These riches, however, have led to one misfortune for the Popes, guaranteeing that the strong Indonesian armed forces maintain their suffocating presence here.
According to a 2005 New York Times investigation, between 1998 and 2004, Freeport paid nearly $20 million to local troops and units, including up to $150,000 to one officer.
The demands for greater autonomy on the part of the Popes threaten the existence of this golden vein and are ruthlessly suppressed.
According to human rights defenders, more than 500,000 Papuas have been killed by the Indonesian military since 1969, and thousands more have been raped, tortured and imprisoned.
According to the Asian Human Rights Commission, the massacres in the native highlands of Papua in the 1970s could be considered genocide.
Last year alone, the Indonesian police arrested more than 3,900 peaceful protesters in the region.
“We will lose everything,” a report published in 2016 by the Brisbane Diocese, contains evidence of the atrocities committed in the previous year, such as summary executions, torture – especially, as another report states, rape and electrocution – and the brutal suppression of peaceful demonstrations.
“It is hard to count the number of victims, because the incidents occur every week,” says Andreas Harrison, a researcher in Indonesia for Human Rights Watch.
The guineas have been protracted, as Papua's resources have attracted the flow of resettlers from other parts of Indonesia.
The 3.5-million population of the province is 83 per cent Christian, but the demographics change as Muslim economic migrants from densely populated Indonesian islands – Java, Sumatra, and Sulawesi – arrive.
Javan shops, “warungi”, sell fried chicken and a mix of gado-gado vegetables served with peanut sauce.
The locals are trying to stand up to the competition.
“Migrants began to sell chicken and vegetables in the traditional market cheaper than the natives of Papua,” explains Abeth Yo, a 25-year-old Paniai, who moved to Jayapur, the provincial capital, for work.
“This is why the natives of Papua, the mother-mother (female) of Papua, lost their marketplace.”
Indonesian President Joko Vidodo, known as the Jokowi, vowed to address inequality and violations of rights in Papua during his 2014 presidential campaign.
On his way to the President's Palace in Jakarta, a former carpenter enlisted the support of 27 of the 29 districts of Papua, including the Paniai.
But there is little change in Papua, and the locals feel loyal.
“Our hearts are broken, because in 2014 we voted for Jokowi, expecting him to live up to our hopes for justice,” Yoo says.
In fact, just two months after the October inauguration, Jokowi Paniai suffered a tragedy.
On December 7, 2014, a group of 11 children was on the street singing Christmas anthems at a fire in Enarotali, when two Indonesian soldiers on a motorcycle broke out of the dark.
The frightened children told them that they should turn on the lights.
According to local pastor Javedt Tebay, one of the soldiers was offended by their tone and later returned with four soldiers.
According to victims and eyewitnesses, soldiers who had been drunk chased the children and beat them with rifles.
Then one of the soldiers shot at a group of children.
One child, Julianus Emo 16, was beaten so badly that he fell into a coma.
A couple of hours later, someone set fire to a government office nearby, and the next day the situation escalated.
About a thousand pope men, women and children gathered in a football field in front of the local police station and the military command centre to demand justice.
They brought their ritual hunting bows and performed the White, the popuasian pago dance, running in circles and playing the bird's song.
Some protesters began to throw stones at the police station and the military base.
When the situation hit, the internal radio service was ordered to “if the crowd resists more than three times, shoot them,” it was said in an official document that was seen by Time magazine correspondents, but was not published in the local media.
The 50 - year - old Jeremias Cayama, head of the Kogo Koto district in Enarotali, felt the danger and called for calm, asking the crowd to go home.
No one wanted to listen to him.
"When I turned around, I suddenly got hit in my left wrist," he told the magazine "TIME," standing on the porch of his brightly painted wooden house.
Kaime still doesn't know who shot him, but he says the bullet came from the shreng of the soldiers gathered.
"There was a crowd, there was a lot of shots," he adds.
A local resident of Alfius Jowa was shot three times, as his cousin, who witnessed the shooting, said.
“I ran up to him and examined his body to make sure it was him,” Johns, who, like many Indonesians, uses only one name, lamented the magazine Time.
"I saw him dead... I kissed him."
General Yotge Mende, Chief Inspector of the Papua Police, told reporters that his officers were just "protecting" their base because it was under attack.
“We must defend ourselves when people are threatening to kill us,” said the Papua Police Commissioner Pujo Sulistio in 2015.
“This is a matter of life and death.”
According to Human Rights Watch, five young protesters were killed and far more wounded.
The news of the murders didn't get to Jakarta until the next day.
Three weeks later, Jokovi gave a passionate speech in Jayapur expressing sympathies to the families of the victims and vowed to address the historical abuse of power in Papua.
“I want this situation to be resolved immediately, never again in the future,” he said.
In October 2016, the Minister for Security, Viranto, said that he would set up a non-judicial organization to put an end to historical human rights violations.
But almost immediately, the excuses went.
“Most of the violations occurred a long time ago.
Some of them occurred in the 1990s or at the beginning of the zero.
The fact is, we certainly want to deal with these violations, but there are procedures that need to be followed,” he said.
Then Viranto gave up his speech with the magazine "TIME" on 5 June in Jakarta, and said that he did not plan to set up an organization to deal with complaints in Papua.
Instead, he said, "All will be decided by a court of law."
Viranto, whom the United Nations had accused of “crimes against humanity” in connection with the death of more than 1,000 people during the bloody East Timor independence vote in 1999, said that 11 human rights violations in Papua had already been resolved, including the Paniai incident.
The families of the victims in Pania met similar claims with grave distrust.
“In the last three years, I have been questioned four times, but there has been no change at all,” says Johannes.
"I'm tired."
He says years later, he's still living in fear.
"I'm scared," he says.
“I'm afraid I'm going to be arrested by the military, I'm afraid I'm going to be shot.”
His brother Jacobus was also of the view that the inhabitants of Pania were afraid to discuss the incident.
He said he was beaten by the military after he helped bury four victims.
“After we buried the bodies, the military came after me,” he says.
The shooting didn't stop.
On Tuesday, the Indonesian police shot at villagers in the nearby Pania district of Deiya.
In a conflict between the villagers and the manager of the construction company, who refused to help bring a man unconscious to the hospital, one person was killed and 17 others were injured, including children.
A 25-year-old man, Ravianos Dove, who drowned while fishing in a nearby river, died on his way to the hospital.
The angry villagers protested in front of the company's construction site office.
According to the police, the villagers threw stones at the officers, who responded with warning shots.
But the locals claim that a mobile brigade (Indonesian Special Forces) started shooting at the crowd and killed a man.
“We've been in such a panic, we're afraid of retaliation,” reported the magazine Time, a 29-year-old Domingue of Badia, who lives near the hospital and has seen the quick delivery of the wounded.
"I've been at home for two days."
The Deyai Parliament demanded that officers involved in the incident be called to account and that the mobile police brigade be withdrawn from the region.
Paniai has always been a sick place for the Indonesian government.
The lack of significant development is a source of dissatisfaction among the tribes of the Mee, Moni, Dani and Damal, which are spread throughout the green central highlands of Papua.
Many have joined the “Movement for a Free Papua” (OPM), a rebel army that claims to defend the rights of the Pope by launching sporadic attacks and raids with kidnappings on Indonesian soldiers.
Some of the top OPM leaders come from Pania, including Thadius Yogi and Daniel Judas Komia.
As a response, in recent years thousands of people have been arrested and arbitrarily detained by the military under the guise of “Protection of national independence”.
Some never came back.
Among the population of Papua Paniai, it is considered “a sad, forgotten place”.
Poverty increases discontent.
A small quantity of rice sold in Enarotali is too expensive for the locals.
The bread is, to the same extent, unavailable.
People here grow everything they eat, mostly a note, as well as some fruit and leafy vegetables.
Agriculture is the work of women, each of whom can care for four to five fields of sweet potatoes.
They usually keep most of the crop for the family, and the rest is sold on the local market.
Ten tubers are worth just 10,000 rupees (75 cents).
Over time, the economic disparities between indigenous papuas and new migrants, who had come in large numbers since the introduction of new flights to Nabir Airport, had increased.
Few existing vacancies are usually held by more educated and well-off migrants.
Papoeas rarely have the money or the necessary skills to run their own competitive business.
“Young people don't want to stay in the village... because there's no work or money here,” says John Gobai, president of the Paniai Tribal Council.
The isolation keeps Papua away from the world's views.
In addition, restrictions on the international media remain severe.
Earlier this year, French journalists Frank Escudie and Basil Lonshan had been deported from Papua for “inconsistencies with the relevant organizations” despite the fact that they had been given rare permission to film.
According to Felim Keene, Deputy Director for Asia, Human Rights Watch, the promises made during the Jokovi campaign to lift media restrictions in order to promote transparency and development have not been met.
“At present, foreign journalists trying to report from rebel eastern Indonesian provinces, Papua and West Papua face new dangers: visa denial and blacklisting,” he said in a statement.
The lack of press attention means that international pressure on the Government of Indonesia is largely limited to Papua's immediate neighbours.
In March, six Pacific States – Tonga, Nauru, Palau, Tuvalu, the Marshall Islands, and Solomon Islands – requested the UN Human Rights Council to investigate “diverse and widespread violations” in Papua, including the Paniai shooting.
The same countries have backed OPM in the past.
A representative of the Ministry of Foreign Affairs of Indonesia, Arramanata Nasir, reneged the group's statement, telling journalists in Jakarta that “In Indonesia there is still a democratic system and a free press, so it would be difficult to cover up evidence of human rights violations.”
Locals want more foreign governments to pay attention to the situation.
When an official delegation from the Netherlands, led by the Netherlands Human Rights Ambassador, Kiis Van Ba ' aar, visited Jayapur on 4 May, the local people broke the silence, saying, “We want freedom,” as the source claims, who also attended the meeting but wanted to remain anonymous.
In Indonesia, new presidential elections will take place in 2019, but the Popes say that they are unlikely to vote for the Jokowi again.
“Jockovi is a man with good intentions, but he is surrounded by people involved in the Paniai shooting,” says Gobai, president of the tribe council.
He wants Jokovi to know that the people of Paniai, apart from living in the shadow of a threat from the greedy army, are in poverty, and their education and health care are in a miserable state.
Gobay says that the Paniai, like the rest of the Papuas, consider their voice for the Jokowi, a debt that he must pay.
“They don't want money, they just want justice,” he says.
Despite threats and intimidation, the families of the victims of the Paniai shooting carried out the last symbolic act of disobedience, burying the body of one of the victims on the plot of land in front of the police and the military station.
Knowing that justice is likely never to be done, at least they will not allow the guilty to forget their crimes.
