The President will decide the order and place of the swearing-in.
Where and as new Russian citizens will swear their allegiance to the Russian Federation, the President will decide - such amendments to the second reading of the relevant law have drawn up a State Duma committee on legislation and Statehood.
A week ago, the deputies planned to make a direct determination of the procedure for swearing in the law.
Children under the age of 18 will be released from the solemn oath, as well as those who are incapacitated, as follows from the amended text of the amendments to the draft law “On the nationality of the Russian Federation”, which the Committee will consider before the second reading on 11 July.
The idea of swearing an oath to become a national of the Russian Federation in place of the formal signature of the documents was supported by President Vladimir Putin on 6 June in a meeting with the Speaker of the State Duma, Vyacheslav Volodin.
The deputies drafted this idea in the form of an amendment to the second reading of the bill, which provides for the annulment of the decision to grant citizenship to those who have subsequently been convicted of a number of terrorist or extremist offences: for example, public calls for terrorism or its public excuse in the media or on the Internet (art. 205.2, para. 2, of the Criminal Code), as well as the hijacking of a plane, train or water transport, but only if the act is linked to terrorism (art. 211, para. 4 of the Code).
According to the bill, his logic was as follows: by issuing citizenship documents, a person is bound by a promise to comply with Russian law - by taking the path of extremism, he is violating that promise.
The bill was submitted to the State in April by the leaders of the Duma factions, Vladimir Vasiliev (Union Russia), Gennady Zyuganov (CPRF), Vladimir Zhirinovsky (LDPR), Sergey Mironov (Just Russia) and the Speaker of the DG Viacheslav Volodin.
On 19 May, the deputies adopted it on first reading.
Last week, the DG Committee on State and Law approved the text of the bill for the second reading, but it has now been redrafted.
It now states that the President of the Russian Federation will set the order of the swearing-in.
Parliamentarians had previously intended to describe the procedure directly in the RF Citizenship Act, stating that the ceremony should take place in a solemn setting in front of the State stamp and the Russian flag in the presence of a representative of the Ministry of Internal Affairs.
However, it was not clear from the text of the bill where such an event was to take place - a list of places where the Russian Federation ' s seal was possible - was regulated by the relevant federal constitutional law.
These include the courts, the offices of the heads of State of the entities, the municipalities, the judges, the prosecutors, the heads of the federal executive, etc.
It's more likely to be a registrar.
The swearing of a solemn oath seeking Russian citizenship will be given after the officials have checked their documents.
But the Russian passport will not be given until after the swearing-in takes place, but it will follow from the refined text.
A week ago, the draft stated that the oath should precede the signing of the decree.
The updated text states that Russia will be sworn in at the age of 18, not at the age of 14.
The rule that incapacitated or limited persons, as well as those who cannot deliver, read or sign the text of the oath by hand, will be maintained.
In addition, the President of the Russian Federation has the right to release from this procedure and “other persons”,
The updated bill also sets out a special procedure for the admission of citizens of Ukraine who are considered to be Russian speakers.
They will have to formally renounce Ukrainian citizenship by submitting an application to the competent body of Ukraine for that purpose.
A notarized copy of the application will have to be handed over to Russian officials.
Rejection of “alien” nationality, as it is, will not be required if it is provided for by an international treaty or if it is not possible “for reasons beyond the control of the person”.
An amendment to the law was proposed by a group of deputies, including the First Vice-Speaker of the DG Ivan Melnikov (CPRF), Natalia Cologna, Pavel Krascheninnikov and Ayrat Farrahov (all “One Russia”).
I think many of you know it's impossible to get a certificate from Ukraine, it's just impossible.
