Bank of England will keep interest rates at 0.25 per cent
The Bank of England is expected to later announce that interest rates will not change after weak economic growth and weakening inflation have shattered rumours of possible increases.
The Bank of England warned that economic growth would remain slow, and left interest rates unchanged among the growing pressure on family income.
The Bank's Monetary Policy Committee (MPC) voted with a score of 6 to 2 to keep the rate at 0.25 per cent, with a smaller number of members in favour of an increase this month, because weak economic growth weakened support for the increase.
In its quarterly inflation report, the bank limited its projections to 1.7 per cent in 2017 and 1.6 per cent in 2018, and warned that the pressure on family income would continue, while inflation was still expected to rise to about 3 per cent in the fall.
The bank, however, warned that an increase in rates in the next few years would be necessary to control the crisis inflation, and said that it was likely that the cost of the loans would have to be raised more than expected in the financial markets.
The members of the committee also voted to abandon part of the huge set of economic development measures launched a year ago as a result of the crisis.
Beginning next February, the bank will close an urgent financing plan for which it provides banks with low-cost loans, even though it reported that it now has to provide an additional 15 billion pounds, up to 115 billion pounds, under the plan.
In the fee protocol, the bank said: “According to the MPC’s main forecasts, the growth of gross domestic product (GDP) remains slow in the near future, while the pressure on real family incomes continues to affect consumption.”
On the issue of rates, he reiterated that a “severe tightening of financial policies” at a “severely greater” level than expected by the markets would be necessary to halt inflation.
At the moment, markets are predicting the first increase in the third quarter of next year, and another in 2020.
But the bank stressed that all the promotions would be “progressive” and “limited.”
The bank's upward projections for this year and the following year are lower than those made in May, which were 1.9 per cent and 1.7 per cent.
The Bank's forecast remained unchanged by 1.8 per cent in 2018.
After the news, the sterling fell relative to the dollar and the euro.
The pound fell by 0.5 per cent to $1.31 and by 0.4 per cent to Euro1.11.
The decision not to change the rate was taken after the recent discouraging growth rate weakened the increased expectation of an increase; GDP then rose by 0.3 per cent in the second quarter, compared to 0.2 per cent in the previous three months.
According to the bank's representative, growth is likely to remain at 0.3% in the third quarter, although it will begin to grow a little later in the year.
The bank’s last report on inflation gave little reason for the joy of the households that had been hit by high inflation and a very small increase in wages: the bank said that the pressure would increase before it fell.
The Bank added that financial policy “can't prevent” the pay-as-you-go in the next few years, but expects that wages will be “significantly” restored by the end of its three-year forecast.
The economy is also determined to grow as a result of the growing demand for British goods, which is due to the low rate of the pound, which offsets part of the lower consumer spending.
The decision was taken a year after last August's rate was reduced to 0.25 per cent after the shocking results of the EU exit referendum, which led to a drop in the pound.
