Beginning in September, patients will have access to a “revolutionary” drug to prevent HIV after the High Court's battle to finance the drug from the State Health Service.
The National Health Service of England has announced that pre-exposure HIV (PREP), a pre-sex pill that has been shown to reduce the risk of infection in persons at risk by an average of 86 per cent, will now be provided by the health service during the initial three-year trial period by about 10,000 people.
It agreed to finance the test after the Court of Appeal had upheld the High Court ' s decision last year, alleging that the National Health Service had an opportunity to pay for the PPE, despite her claim that it should be financed by the local authorities.
This step, which was announced on Thursday, was described as “the most important innovation” by the President of the National Health Service of England, Simon Stevens, and the National AIDS Control Office (NAT) called it a “turn point.”
Prior to the full launch of the program all over England, by April 2018, venereal dispensaries in London, Brighton, Manchester, Liverpool, and Sheffield will be among the first to register, and more of them will join the program in October.
Pre-exposive prevention (PREP) is a pre-sex drug course to reduce the risk of HIV infection.
Studies have shown that PEI significantly reduces the risk of HIV infection among people at risk.
When taking pre-sex POPs in humans, there are enough specific drugs to prevent HIV infection.
Such drugs can be taken daily or not later than two hours before sex.
Patients eligible for medication include gay and bisexual men, transgender men and people whose partners are HIV-positive and do not receive successful treatment.
Disponents will select suitable participants who have agreed to participate in the study, including men, women, transgenderers and persons of whom partners are unknown whether their HIV status is limited by anti-retroviral therapy.
People who live and are assigned to a general practitioner in England will also be able to apply for a potential participation in the nearest STD in the programme.
The programme will cost £10 million, and the National Health Service of England has signed a drug contract this week after the international tender for purchase.
The study is designed to assess the full potential of the PEI by collecting clinical data on the target audience of the drug, its absorptiveness and its application on a large scale.
“This critical innovation should complement and reinforce the wide-ranging and increasingly successful efforts to prevent HIV.
This is another milestone in more than three decades of success in the fight against one of the major health threats facing humanity.
Deborah Gold, president of the NAT, said: “This is a turning point in the fight against HIV.
The PEI, by properly targeting people who need help and are at risk, offers an opportunity to change the state of the HIV epidemic in England.
