The Presidential Council for Human Rights (HRC) has, on behalf of Vladimir Putin, developed proposals to strengthen the independence of the judiciary.
The HRC suggests that the powers of the presidents of the courts be limited and that they be elected.
For the Courts of Appeal and Cassation, the HRC wishes to introduce special districts that will not be linked to the administrative and territorial division in the Russian Federation.
The Supreme Court should also present its proposals in the context of the presidential mandate.
The HRC has finalized proposals that will enhance the independence of Russian justice.
This work was carried out by the HRC on behalf of Vladimir Putin on 3 January 2017, which the President gave after a meeting with the Council.
At a meeting with the Council on 8 December 2016, individual cases of arbitrariness were discussed, as well as problems of public control in places of detention (see OS, 9 December).
The work of the HRC has resulted in 25 proposals, which address both the issues of ensuring the independence of the judiciary and the identification of miscarriage of justice, as well as the financing of the courts and legal education.
One of the ideas of the Kremlin human rights defenders was to limit the powers of the presidents of the courts in order to enhance the independence of the rest of the judiciary.
If the candidate for the post of judge had successfully passed the competition and had received the support of the judicial community, the President of the Court, in the opinion of the Human Rights Council, should submit him for appointment without the right to refuse, as the law currently permitted.
It is also proposed that the President should not be allowed to distribute cases between the judges.
Doing it, experts say, can be a specially written computer program.
The HRC also considers that the president is not entitled to “predetermine the results of the judge's qualification, initiate disciplinary action, or make decisions on the establishment of additional material payments”.
At the same time, the President's Council considers it necessary to move to “elect the presidents of the courts themselves” and to “power them for a relatively short period of time with a mandatory rotation”.
All presidents of the courts (republic to district) are now appointed by the President for a period of six years at the request of the President of the Supreme Court of the Russian Federation.
In order to protect the judges from the pressure of the regional administrations, the HRC proposes to re-organize the appeal and cassation before the courts of general jurisdiction.
Their structure is now linked to the administrative-territorial division in the Russian Federation.
The HRC states that “there is a need to ensure that individual courts of appeal and cassation are organized not at the level of the regional courts in the constituent entities of the Russian Federation, but in the judicial districts”.
The experts are based on the practice of arbitral tribunals.
There are “judiciary districts” that do not correspond to the administrative division in the Russian Federation, but thus guarantee greater independence from regional officials who have difficulty in using the “telephone law”.
The HRC ' s peace judges propose to be strengthened by the people ' s jurors to deal with some of the “classifications of civil and administrative cases” with them.
