Italy is tightening the tone with respect to the ships of NGOs that save migrants.
Italy warned the NGOs that own rescue vessels in the Mediterranean that they would not be able to continue their work unless they complied with the new rules governing their operations.
“If NGOs fail to comply with the new code of conduct, it is hard to say whether they will be able to continue their activities,” said the Minister of the Interior, Mario Minniti, in an interview with the Turin daily Stampa.
A warning was given by Minnichi the day after the Italian authorities confiscated a vessel belonging to the German humanitarian organization Jugend Retette, on the suspicion that its crew was actually cooperating with traffickers and facilitating illegal immigration.
The humanitarian organization, which had worked for only a year, had declined to comment on the substance of the detailed charges brought against it by the Italian prosecutor Ambrojo Kartozio.
“For us, saving human life is and will remain the top priority, so we are very sorry that we cannot continue to work in the search and rescue zone,” states the organization's statement on social media.
"We will only be able to evaluate all the charges that have been made now after we have gathered all the information and can assess the situation."
The Italian authorities have been following the Juventa, a ship belonging to the Jugend Retette, since October.
His crew is suspected of having taken migrants on board by lifeboats, who had been sent directly to them by traffickers, and allowing smugglers to leave with boats that they could use again.
At least one such meeting is expected to take place within 1.3 miles of the Libyan coastline, as stated in the prosecution file, the content of which was published in the Italian media.
The crew is suspected of violating the orders of the Italian shore authorities, which control rescue operations in the zone, more out of humanitarian zeal than for any other reason.
The Code of Conduct presupposes, in the main, that the “Juventa”-type vessels will have a member of the Italian police who will monitor their activities.
So far, only three of the nine NGOs involved in search and rescue have agreed to abide by the Code: Save the Children, the Maltese MOAS, and the Pro-Activa Open hugs from Spain.
The latter stated on Thursday that it considered the new rules to be unnecessary, but acceptable, provided that they did not cause any “significant change or interference” with its rescue operations.
Among those who refused to sign, there is the Nobel Prize-winning MSF.
In the meantime, Minnichi said that the dramatic decline in recent weeks in the number of migrants coming to Italy as a result of rescue operations indicated that efforts to support the Libyan Coast Guard and co-operation with local mayors had borne fruit.
"In the last days we have begun to see the light at the end of the tunnel," the minister said.
He reported on plans for further negotiations with the Libyan mayors on economic development initiatives and with Chad, Niger and Mali on measures to reduce the number of migrants leaving those countries in the hope of reaching Europe.
