The authorities of the Russian Federation have recently significantly intensified their policies in the Libyan direction, and delegations of the opposing Libyan parties have joined in their visits to Moscow.
The head of the Russian Contact Group for an Illiberian settlement under the Ministry of Foreign Affairs of the Russian Federation and the State Duma, Assistant Head of the Chechen Republic, Lev Degov, told us what the objectives of Moscow in the region are and on whom he puts his stake.
The contact group on Libya, which you are chairing, is almost unknown.
Let's say the contact group on Ukraine -- everyone knows about it.
And here is a veil of mystery.
What exactly do you do, what goals do you pursue?
The Contact Group was established at the initiative of the Ministry of Foreign Affairs of the Russian Federation and the State Duma.
It is run by the Deputy Minister for Foreign Affairs, Mikhail Bogdanov, and Adam Delimhanov.
The latter is authorized to work in the Libyan direction by the Speaker of the State of Vyacheslav Volodin.
The reason for the formation of the group was the arrest in Libya of a Russian tanker, the Chebotarev Mechanic (in September 2015 there were 11 people on board).
We've been thinking about how to help the crew.
At that time, a contact group of military experts, representatives of the State, was set up, and our work was supported by the Head of Chechnya, Ramzan Qadirov.
And how did you manage it?
Since I have been working in Libya since 2008, I have been asked to lead the group.
Our activities have not been limited to the release of sailors from Chebotarev's Mechanics.
We have been able to establish contacts with representatives of all major groups opposing each other in the Libyan conflict - and from Tripoli (where the UN-recognized government is based under Faiz Saraj. - "Oz") and to Tobrook (the branch of Parliament that opposes the Government and supports marshal Khalifa Haftar, who controls the eastern part of Libya. - "Oz").
Thanks to the active participation of Ahmed Metig (the Libyan Vice-Prime Minister) we were able to quickly agree on the release of Russian sailors.
It was then decided to make more effective use of those contacts, to set up a contact group.
Its mission is to analyse the situation, to identify key factors and players, and to engage with all parties to the conflict.
I want to stress that in Libya we do not want to be associated with any of the parties to the conflict; we are engaged in a dialogue with all.
How many people are in the contact group and how many are in Libya?
The contact group is now composed of five people.
Among them are people with experience in the security sector, including the Ministry of Defence.
We also want to include in the regional team the representatives of the Institute of the Middle East Rana.
There is no permanent presence of any of our staff in Libya, which is not yet necessary.
Is there any Russian military advisors, instructors in Libya now?
And if so, on whose side?
There are no Russian military professionals in Libya.
All conversations and publications about this are not true.
But your contact group includes the ex-military...
Yes, and their presence is necessary.
Like when we go to hot spots.
Or cities that have been closed to a certain point for us, such as Misurat (where militias are based, which have played a role in the overthrow of the Libyan leader Muammar Gaddafi in 2011 and which have significantly intensified in the years to come).
We arrived in Misurat in January this year.
We've been scared, told that there's a lot of Islamist, terrorist.
But it was important for us to take stock of the situation, analyse the real military potential, who is responsible, why such rumours are going on, what the real role of Islamists is.
In Misurat, we met with all the elements involved in the destruction of the IG in Sirte (in December 2016, this city on the Mediterranean coast was taken away from the Russian-prohibited “Islamic State” - UO).
We wanted to see them, meet them, check out the information that they played a crucial role in the destruction of the IG in Libya, not the Khalifa Haftar, who attributed to himself.
And what is your conclusion?
"The Islamic State" in Libya won not Haftar?
He didn't do it.
Haftar had operations on the other front, in Benghazi.
And with the IG in Sirte, the structures under the government in Tripoli fought.
And by the way, we've invited to Russia the people who did this anti-terrorist operation.
And they came - the visit lasted from 19 to 23 April this year, and the Libyan delegation was received in the Federation Council, in Douma, MIDE, and Rosgwardia.
You, as we understand it, are found in all the Libyan regions, and you are probably imagining the sentiments of local elites and field commanders.
Do you think it will be possible to implement the ceasefire agreements, the elections reached at the end of July in Paris by Khalifa Haftar and Faiz Saraj?
Or again, as has been the case many times in the past, the agreements will be shattered, the fighting will resume, the parties will try alone to take power?
The fact that Saraj and Haftar have agreed to another meeting has been a good signal to us, not long ago.
In the recent past, both leaders have been very negative about each other.
And as for Russia's position...
It is often said and written that Moscow is actively supporting the Haftara, and many believe it.
We faced this situation when we were in Misurat, and Haftar was on the same day on board the Russian air carrier "Admiral Kuznetsov."
It was a coincidence.
But in Misurat, they didn't believe in coincidence.
We were told, "You must be very brave people who came to us today."
But our task is to show that we do not support only the Haftar, we are engaged in a dialogue with all the key actors in the conflict in Libya.
You and Haftar have been in touch.
Does understanding with Russian partners at the human, emotional level make it easier for him to go to the USSR twice?
And, by the way, does Haftar know Russian?
Russian, if he knows, it's very relative.
But the fact that he learned from us, of course, makes it easier to talk to him.
And by the way, it's not just him.
When we talk to the military in Tripoli and Misurat, we meet the generals who have studied either in Russia or in the Soviet Union.
And now they speak Russian very well.
And they're reaching for Russia, and they're kind of nostalgic about it.
Do you consider it likely that the arms embargo imposed on Libya will be lifted as soon as possible?
Are your Libyan interlocutors interested in the supply of Russian weapons?
Of course, but, as I said, we don't take sides in this conflict, and we don't want to arm some to the detriment of others.
We would like everyone to be in a similar position.
With regard to the arms embargo, there have been constant calls from the Libyans for Russia to help lift it.
The process of drafting a constitution is now under way in Libya.
We hope that the parties will reach compromises, reach an internal consensus.
Then the election will take place, as was said at the Saraj and Haftara meetings.
If the elections are held and legitimate power is finally elected (and none of the parties now has that status), the question of lifting the arms embargo can be raised in the UN Council.
To raise this issue now is pointless and dangerous, it will only lead to an escalation of the conflict.
Recently, the media reported that Italy, faced with the problem of African refugees coming from Libya, felt left behind by EU allies.
Can Moscow, in this situation, help Italian partners by using its ties to the Libyans?
How realistic, for example, is it that the Haftar forces will take control of the coast and put an end to the business of smugglers moving immigrants to Europe?
A very timely question.
We're actively working on it.
The Italians need Russia's support because Moscow is conducting a dialogue at the same time with Haftar, Saraj, Misurat, and the south.
The tribes in southern Libya play a major role in this matter, and they are ready to cooperate with Russia.
Is it a question of the south to stop the flow of migrants in long-distance?
So, by the way, they've been unrolling back the buses of Nigerian migrants?
That's what we're trying to do.
But it's not easy.
Some clans and groups are interested in continuing these flows.
We hope to help bring the South together in the negotiation process between Saraj, Haftar and the tribes of the South.
But first, we would like to see a common view on this issue between Haftar and Saraj.
The head of government in Tripoli, Faiz Saraj, is considered to be an Islamist, a supporter of the establishment of sharia in the country.
How radical is he?
Would that not be an obstacle to building relations with Russia or the West?
I'll tell you my personal opinion of him.
In my view, he is, on the contrary, an opponent of radical Islam.
But Islamists are part of his coalition.
Yes, but it is his own position that Libya must be a perfectly normal country - a moderately Islamic, open world.
And he is also active in the fight against terrorists.
Where did he get that reputation?
It is created by those countries that do not want Russia to interact with Tripoli.
Tripoli is the capital, and there is the legislature, the executive and the judiciary.
There's a national oil corporation, a national bank, and other public entities.
Of course, some countries wanted us to stay out of it.
And we mixed all the cards with them and started to interact actively with both Tripoli and Tobrook.
We are already reaping the benefits of this work: Rosneft has entered into a cooperation agreement with the Libyan State Oil Company, NOC.
The Director of NOC, Mustafa Sanalla, with whom the head of Rosnefti, Igor Sechin, made a deal, is directly from Tripoli.
And two weeks ago, there was the first shipment of Libyan oil to Rosneft.
What will Russia do with it?
I guess we'll re-sell.
What other economic interests do Russia have in Libya?
Plans to re-sign the contracts under Muammar Gaddafi.
These include, inter alia, previous transport agreements (railway construction), energy (electrification) and a number of others.
Do the Libyans have anything to pay for?
Well, they have oil.
So this is the oil-for-service scheme, as in the case of Iran?
I don't know what the scheme will be, I don't do that right now.
In fact, the economy for Russia in Libya is not the most important.
We're actually doing peacekeeping work there.
For us, it is important to stop the bloodshed, to help the Libyans to negotiate among themselves so that they can establish order, and Libya has ceased to be an enabling environment for the development of terrorism.
For Russia, that is the main task to help the Libyan people and to get the terrorists out of there.
Do you have any data on the presence in Libya (now or before) of radical militants from Russia or other countries of the former USSR?
One of the tasks of our contact group was to find out.
I met with a representative of the Libyan State Security Committee, who said that, to date, no one from Russia or from other countries of the former USSR was there.
He said that he had about 50,000 phone records of Islamist and radical groups (in Libya - OS) and no Russian speech there.
And from what States, then, are these militants?
I don't want to go into that detail.
Then we'll put the question differently.
How many of the Islamic militants in Libya are the Libyans themselves?
There are virtually no Libyans among them, not more than 5 per cent.
The rest are incoming.
Can Moscow hold intra-Libish talks on the example of Paris?
There are plans for that.
We are engaged in intensive talks with the Libyans, a number of delegations from Libya have already visited Moscow, and have offered to visit Moscow or Grozny again.
And when can such negotiations take place?
It's hard to say right now.
A number of visits have yet to take place, and I hope that the time and place of the talks will be clear.
