A new kind of start-up in the area of staff is now emerging, helping companies to find out how their employees feel.
By developing and licensing software that is designed to measure the involvement of staff members, they allow companies to make express interviews, to refer to certain teams and population groups, to offer staff anonymity and hotlines for complaints, and, in some cases, to allow informants to pass the top management and direct contact with the directorate.
"Now we have tools like Strava and Fitbit to monitor health, and where is Fitbit for your company?," says Jim Barnett, co-founder and president of the Glint startup in Redwood City, whose analytical programs are being used by companies to measure employee involvement.
Errett said that she had reached a better understanding of what her staff thought and felt in three years of Glint use.
In addition to the express polls and questionnaires of certain teams, the product offers the company's heat map and shows which units have more complaints and which managers have a low rating of approval, which allows it to understand why.
The companies are somewhat aware of the need to control the workplace, or they will become the next Uber, who was involved in the scandal when a former employee posted a blog that described the aggressive environment in which those who had expressed discontent were punished.
For start-ups like "Glint", this desire to control the situation is an opportunity for profit-making business.
The "Let's Talk About Pay" Internet Portal, dedicated to financial technology, estimates that the global governance, regulation and alignment industry may cost over $118.7 billion by 2020.
The "Convercent" start-up in Denver, Colorado, helping companies to prevent and detect bad behavior, noted a small increase in interest and activity earlier this year, amid the loss of Uber's reputation.
Convercent has almost 600 clients, including Airbnb, Microsoft, and Tesla.
Uber has recently emerged as a client.
Like Glint, Convercent allows companies to send individual interviews of staff views, collect confidential answers in real time, and view heat maps of problem areas.
It also provides a hotline for anonymous text messages, which allows staff to report bad behaviour.
And if the top manager is involved, the complaints go straight to the office.
“The Court of Public Opinion has overtaken the powers of the inspectors,” said Patrick Quinlan, the founder and president of Convercent.
If it turns out that the company is ill-treated or unethical, even if the inspector does not intervene, the company may face costly consequences in the form of client boycotts, outflows and lawsuits, Queenlan reported.
Ruby Tuesday, a network of restaurants with more than 25,000 employees in 500 establishments, used Convercent for over a year to make sure that the staff were aware of the rules and procedures, and to suggest a simple way to contact the company's head office.
In the past, if the staff member wanted to report the problem, he or she had to look for a telephone number or a head office e-mail, file a formal complaint and hope that it would be taken seriously.
This was often a frightening and awkward experience, reported James Vitrano, the head of the legal office of Ruby Tuesday, who said that there was no normal way to monitor staff complaints.
Now that the company is using the Convercent service, the problems that were previously hidden from managers in offices in other cities or states – such as discrimination, charisma, and unfair pay – can be quickly detected and addressed.
“I can get closer to a holistic, comprehensive understanding of the situation of the staff,” said Vitrano, who manages the Ruby Tuesday risk management team.
“And we are protecting our shareholders from legal proceedings with the staff.”
According to Queenland, companies began to take more seriously the ethics, values, and involvement of employees in 2002, after Arthur Andersen's accounting firm collapsed because of ethical irregularities as a result of Dela Enron.
But it was only when “social networks have become more common” that the companies realized that they would not be able to keep their dirty underwear from spreading the virus online.
“Before starting to use technology to control ethics, people used hope as a strategy,” he said.
Both "Glint" and "Convercent" offer their software as a service, charging companies regularly for the use of their products.
It's a business model and an opportunity that won the approval of venture investors who supported both startups.
In February, "Convercent" received $10 million in funding from firms such as "Sapphire Ventures" and "Tola Capital", bringing the company's total capital to $47 million.
Glint received $10 million in November from Besser Venture Partners, bringing the company's total capital to $60 million.
These investments are hardly surprising given the interconnected nature of companies, culture and venture capital.
The growing volume of research shows that today's employees expect more of their jobs than they did before.
In markets with strong competition, such as the Silicon Valley, high wages, and interesting projects, they are just the minimum necessary.
The employees want to feel that they are accepted and appreciated and that they are devoting their time to companies with a positive mission.
“When people are happy to work in a company, they feel that they are being heard, and that the work they do is producing results, they are more committed to making such a company a success,” says Nina McQueen, the vice president of global benefits and satisfaction at LinkedIn, where both Convercent and Glint are used.
Investors earn income when companies from their portfolio are doing well; business from companies is doing well when employees are loyal and involved.
If third-party analytical tools promise to increase the commitment and engagement of staff, it is not surprising that they find support.
According to cultural professionals in the workplace, it is important to have data on the involvement of staff.
But the data is useless until the company's trustees take action.
In fact, if a company asks for feedback, it can create the impression that change is coming.
And if change doesn't come fast enough, or if it doesn't come at all, there may be frustration, and the staff will lose interest.
“If you're going to ask for 4,000 offers, you should be ready to hold 4,000 interviews,” says Russell Rut, president of the management firm of Kotter International, who had to see companies make a mistake, relying too much on data collection.
“Because if you don't go to the end, the staff will wonder, ‘Do you hear me?
Do you care?
And if you don't care, why don't I care?"
According to Errett, Madison Reed, which is currently conducting monthly interviews with staff, is in a position to take action on the same day that someone is reporting the problem with the help of Glint.
And, after collecting feedback from the staff, dissatisfied with the speed of decision-making and the quality of communication, it was able to restructure a number of teams within the company and introduce a communication training to solve the problem.
Ruby Tuesday is learning new things about its employees and hopes that in the long run it will be more effective in holding staff in an industry known for high turnover.
“If you do not try to create a culture of transparency, you will lose people,” Vitrano said.
If you lose people, you lose clients.
And if you lose clients, you lose companies.
