Ah, I love archives!"
For a man so passionate about old papers, to get support from the National Foundation and the English Arts Council, and to live in the castle for four months ("I've been there a little bit") seems too good to be true.
Rhoades spent all day studying the "new" Victorian castle, walking through the archives, and looking at numerous treasures of property and antiquities - for example, the heads of hyenas on walls or bottles that had been in the crest for centuries.
He was walking through the park and the ruins of the old castle, talking to the foresters, the gardeners, and sometimes the painters who worked on the illustrations of his book.
Then at night, he "drinked whiskey and sat down to write."
The history of Scotty's castle is not well known, because the National Foundation only gained full access to it in 2006, when the last heir, Elizabeth Hassy, died.
When Rhoades arrived ten years later, the staff was just beginning to deal with the archive, which he described as "what the aristocrats had been on the attic for centuries."
The journals, the letters of the British Empire, the maps that show who owned what you think land disputes are boring, Rhoades says, but this is what two families fought for.
It happens, guys!"
In some of the history of the book, the castle becomes the starting point for the wider search in English history: for example, in "The Worker", the hero leaves the newly built castle to join the Christian Revolution of 1381.
"There is evidence of a mutiny that took place at the castle in 1380, in a book called "The knightly families of Kent and Sussex," Rhoades says.
"The Crusade Revolt began in these places, and I thought the rebellion was a good start.
Maybe they were bound."
Other stories are closely related to the history of the castle, for example, the "People of the Church", which tells us about the Jesuit priest that the Darryl family had been hiding for seven years during the English Reformation.
Or "Smuggling" about an 18th-century smuggler, Arthur Darrell, who is believed to have staged his own funeral by filling a coffin with stones (this was discovered a few years later when the coffin was dug up).
The Darrells are the favorite family of Rhoades who lived in Scotty: "The Gentlemans seem to have been a perfect swindler, always in debt, and spend money on things they couldn't afford.
In different generations, Darryl men have solved their debt problems by marrying rich older women - I picture them as a company of handsome guys who know how to care for the heirs of big fortunes."
After finishing work at the castle, Rhoades is looking for other ways to get a unique writing experience.
He lived for two weeks in the countryside, where he wrote a graphic novel about Eliamyanmeaki, a place where the sanatorium was in the early 20th century, and then it was re-growing in the forest.
But Scotty remains a special place for him.
"I was sad to leave," he says.
"I felt like, damn it, I have to get back to real life."
