Red meat, dairy products, and chocolate can help to make the WBC easier.
Red meat and chocolate are considered a nightmare for your digestive tract.
But recent studies suggest the opposite: a diet rich in meat proteins and dairy products can help to alleviate the symptoms of inflammable intestinal diseases.
It is an incurable disease that affects about 1.3 million people in the United States and 300,000 in the United Kingdom, leading to a colicing and swelling of the abdomen, chronic or bloody diarrhea, loss of weight, and extreme fatigue.
Normally, in order to mitigate symptoms, patients are advised to avoid meat and dairy, but researchers at the University of Washington have found that the main amino acid triptophan is contributing to the production of immune cells that increase intestinal tolerance.
The lead researcher, Dr. Marco Colonna, explained that the immune cells in the intestine are making sure that no harm can be done to the intestines.
Cells capable of triggering an inflammatory process are balanced by cells that increase tolerance by protecting the body without harming sensitive tissues.
If the balance is too disrupted in the direction of inflammation, it can lead to inflammatory intestinal diseases.
Experiments have shown that mice that have a certain bacterium in their intestines have a growing cell tolerance.
And this bacteria needs a triptophan, one of the building elements of the protein, to start the appearance of these cells.
Professor Colonna said, "We have established a link between one type of bacteria, Lactobacilus reuteri, which is part of the normal intestinal microbiomy, and the development of a population of cells that promote tolerance.
The more the triptophan was in the mice's diet, the more these immune cells they had."
He suggested that the same would work for humans: a combination of L. reuteri and a rich triptophan diet can lead to a more tolerant and less prone to inflammation in the intestines.
Postdock Dr. Luisa Cervantes-Barraganwas, studying a variety of tolerant immune cells, found that one group of test mice had these cells, and the other group, which belonged to the same line but was not.
She suggested that the difference could be caused by microbial intestines - bacterial, viral, and fungi communities that usually live in the gastrointestinal tract.
The DNA of the intestine cells was sequented, and six types of bacteria were found present in mice with immune cells but not in mice without them.
Mice grown in a sterile environment that did not have a good microbiomy and did not develop this kind of immune cell have L. reuteri, and they have immunized cells.
To understand how bacteria affect the immune system, researchers raised L. reuteri in a liquid environment, and then moved small portions of the liquid, free of bacteria, to the unsustainable immune cells separated from mice.
Immune cells have become more tolerant cells.
When the active component was separated from the liquid, it turned out to be a by-product of triptophane processing, known as idol-3-milk acid.
When researchers doubled the number of triptophans in mice's food, the number of these cells increased by about 50 per cent, but when the level of triptophane was halved, the number of cells also halved.
Dr. Cervantes-Barragan explains that humans have the same tolerant cell as mice, and most of us have L. reuteri in their gastrointestinal tract.
It is not known whether the by-products of the L. reuteri are contributing to the development of human cells, as are mice, but people with inflammable intestinal diseases have been found to be defective in the genes associated with the triptophan.
She says, "Perhaps we need to boost the development of these cells, because these cells affect inflammatory processes on the inner surface of the intestines.
High levels of triptophan, if L. reuteri is present, can potentially lead to an expansion of their population. "
