The White House Requisition cost the taxpayers thousands of dollars.
According to the records of the armed forces given to the magazine Time, the White House's decision last month to bring a Marine Helicopter to the South Lawn for an event dedicated to American industrial production cost the taxpayers $24,000.
The white-green Sikorsky VH-3D, known as "Marine One", when the president is on board, became a central element of the event held in the White House on 17 July, at which American construction programmes were shown.
President Donald Trump, Vice-President Mike Pens, and the White House's top officials have examined the technology products from all 50 states.
A helicopter made in Connecticut was placed next to a boat from Maine, a fire truck from Wisconsin, and a cargo truck from Mississippi.
According to the records of the First Marine Helicopter Squadron (HMX-1), the unit responsible for managing the helicopter, the White House Military Department ordered the presence of a helicopter in a private order, or “FRAGO”, only 36 hours before the helicopter landed on the South Lawn on the occasion of a “unusual” event.
“I just wanted you to know that you know, because this is an unusually well-publicized event,” wrote Commander HMX-1 in an e-mail to his supervisor, the first Deputy Air Force Chief, on the eve of the event.
The letter indicated that the helicopter would arrive in the South Lawn at about 7 a.m. on 17 July to attend an event scheduled for 3 p.m. and stay there until the lawn was released between 6 p.m. and 9 p.m. on the same day.
The letter adds that if departure from the White House is delayed, a second crew will be required to return in accordance with the time limits.
The first crew accompanied the helicopter during the event, while the guard of the unit remained close to the aircraft while it was on the ground.
It was not clear from the records received by the magazine “TIME” whether the second crew was required.
The Hatch Act prohibits federal employees from using public property for political purposes.
According to the records, HMX-1 specified whether the activity was in conflict with that order.
“We asked, among other things, if it was a violation of Hatch's law, and they said no,” the commander wrote.
“You seem to have nowhere to go,” the Deputy Chief replied.
The "Done in America" event was declared an official event by the White House and was not subject to the Hatch Act.
But even formal events have political notes.
During the event, the President made an effort to advance the reform of health, which was at the time in the drafting of the Senate, and praised attempts to regulate government regulations.
The use of aircraft, known as "Marine One" and "air Force One" for political purposes, is hardly a new phenomenon.
Presidents are required to use them for travel.
But it's not unusual to ask for them alone in the interest of photofidelity.
Trump was already the subject of discussion in February, when the president's plane drove in the background during his first election rally in Melbourne, Florida, and his Twitter account was full of complaints about the use of the president's plane by his predecessor.
"The White House is thrilled with the show "Make America," which featured products from 50 states made by American workers from American material," said Lyndsey Walters, the White House's Deputy Spokesperson.
HMX-1 crews often fly around the Washington Agglomeration and on the South Lawn to train the president of the United States to transport to the White House to an inch.
When Trump was at the G-20 summit in Germany in early July, HMX-1 conducted 58 training landings at the White House.
According to one of the officials, the flight carried out for the "Done in America" event was counted to the crew for the necessary training flights in a month.
The unit's helicopters also overflyed 11 additional hours on that day as part of the “non-presidential support tasks”.
According to the White House, the taxpayers did not spend on any of the other items represented at the event.
A representative of Sikorsky reported that the company had not participated in the South Lawn Helicopter Demonstration.
HMX-1 does not account for the budget for the presidential flights, and it is difficult to determine the exact amount spent on the event.
But according to the time rate of the Department of Defense for the fiscal year 2017, the rate of reimbursement for the Department of Defense for the VH-3D is US$24,380 per flight hour.
The unit records that the flight time in the air was 30 minutes each way from its airstrip at the Quantico Marine Airbase in Virginia.
The White House claims that the real cost of using the helicopter is much lower than that rate.
“The calculation of the cost to the taxpayers, based on an estimated rate of reimbursement, is very wrong,” says Walters.
“These indicative rates include personnel, services and many other irreversible costs that are included in the annual allocation.”
According to a study carried out in 2015 by the RAND Corporation, the rates of reimbursement do not include the cost of personnel, but do take into account the cost of fuel, maintenance and the costs specified in the contract.
At the time, the former White House Press Secretary, Sean Spicer, spoke out to defend the use of the helicopter for the event.
“The idea is to show this week the things done in America,” Spicer said.
“And I know that Sikorsky and Connecticut are very proud of the fact that they contribute to national security, and that there are, I suppose, hundreds, if not thousands, of people whose job depends on it.
And I think, like most Americans, that we are all proud of this helicopter and other military equipment that so many Americans have been working tirelessly on.
Therefore, of course, it is entirely appropriate to pay attention to this.”
It was not clear whether Trump interacted with the helicopter by inspecting the South Lawn during the event, but he was exactly in the driver's seat in the fire truck.
Inside the White House, Trump approached the company's representatives, making a joke with the press about his own fleet of the company's products.
"I know very well "Sikorsky," the president said. "I have three."
